<br>
Rofl... huh??  Umm, necros getting chewed up on an add?  Are you sure you know what a necromancer can do?  My necro can handle numerous adds, and subsequently annihilate them.  A mage is the class that gets chewed up on &quot;adds&quot;.  <br>
<br>
Necros really don't need to group, and get way more experience soloing.  A mage HAS to group post 60, or they will get 0 experience.  Necros can solo better by far, and when dealing with undead pets, have a better pet as well.<br>
<br>
Mages are MUCH better in burst damage, and are great in Trial Groups.  Once made a trial group with 3 mages, and cleric, enchanter, tank.... it was BRUTAL!!  The mobs were punished badly.  Mages can make fools out of anyone in a trial scenario, bar none.  <br>
<br>
Mages have better pets, and can create pets rather cheaply.  Mages, however, can not mitigate damage, and their pets can not &quot;mez-tank&quot; mobs in Higher PoP Tiers.<br>
<br>
Mages are also very good on green conning mobs.  With epic pet, you can devastate some of the green zones for loot, and such.<br>
<br>
Necros have vastly superior mana regeneration, and superior dmg/mana ratio spells via dots.<br>
<br>
Necro/Mage is a great combination.  I have had alot of fun in both class sides of this duo.  But 2 necros are just sick, sick, sick :-)<br>
<br>
As for proccing items, etc.  They are nice, but really don't help in choosing a class.  You can always bumb some summoned items off from the local &quot;Nexus Mage&quot;. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=etadanikm>EtadanikM</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 70<br> <font color=#333333>(11/29/02 4:55:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7992.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mage vs. Necro</span><hr size=1> Well the thing you gotta realize is that while all solo classes got hit hard in PoP, alot of them got seriously buffed for groups.  I certainly wouldn't say that druids or mages should need to solo in the new expansion, because personally these two classes have attained abilities in PoP that make them top-end grouping classes.<br>
<br>
Now look at the necromancer class.  The class has never been just about offensive abilities like mages were.  We never were the be-all end-all damage dealer in a group and never will be.  This has ALWAYS been made up by the fact that necros could solo extremely well and were very versatile in groups in that we could help enchanters mez, help clerics heal, etc.  This balanced the necromancer class.  This balance no longer exists.<br>
<br>
Now most necros in the tier 2 and above planes are nothing more than damage dealers.  A mob comes, the necro sicks his pet, casts two dots, and nukes a bit.  There's no difference between what he is and what a mage is, except a necro is not meant to be a mage - we not only do not match a mage in pure offensive power, but we DON'T WANT TO be a mage with high offensive power.  If we wanted to nuke a mob a couple of times a fight and send our pet why not roll a mage? This is not the necro's role and few necros like it.<br>
<br>
When I said soloing is becoming obsolete, I did not mean that soloing is wholly impossible (though it certainly is in some higher tier planes), but that it's not becoming viable as a means of exp gain.  Sure, you still see some necros soloing in PoValor, but they're the last ones who just won't accept the fact that necro soloing is quickly coming to an end.  PoValor is also pretty much the last zone where necro soloing is still &quot;barley&quot; alive - e.g. crystal golems can be soloed by necros, still, but most anyting else cannot.<br>
<br>
Previously, necros prided in the idea that we can solo as well as groups made exp.  That's what made necros great - that's the reason why many people played necros, because we are SELF-RELIANT.  No matter how you argue that EQ should be a grouping game, you cannot deny that necros have been great soloers for the past 3 years and that the necro class is in many ways the last bastion of hope for people who liked Everquest but didn't like the way groups worked in EQ (where you need a slower, a tank, an enchanter, a cleric, blah blah blah).  Maybe this perspective is wrong, but if it is many people shared it, and now that VI is taking it away, many people are also going away from EQ/necromancers in general.  This is because for the last three years this has been the way the necro is played.  Play a necro from 1-60 and you will find that soloing is what the necro was made to do.  Now to suddenly change this 61+ is too late.  People so long entrenched in the style of a necromancer can not suddenly make the transition, or do not want to.<br>
<br>
Don't make the mistake of thinking that mages are hit harder than necros in this.  Mages, no matter how you put it, were always more group-oriented than necros.  Sure, you had the odd mage who enjoyed soloing more than grouping, but for every one mage who enjoyed soloing more than grouping two necros enjoyed soloing more than grouping.  Necros are the *preemptory* class for soloing, and thus hits to soloing for us are like tremendous blows, whereas for other classes it might be just a &quot;slap in the face&quot;, to use the old term.  An equal analogy can be made of pets: if VI nerfed pets in general, mages are hit hardest of all, because mages are the *preemptory* class for pets.<br>
<br>
<br>
